CFL-013: Guard CIccTagArray copy ctor + Cleanup against uninitialized/poisoned state (CWE-908/CWE-416)

CIccTagArray copy constructor does not initialize m_TagVals or m_nSize
before the `if (tagAry.m_nSize)` check. When m_nSize is 0 (or the calloc
fails on the else-less path), both fields remain uninitialized. The
destructor calls Cleanup() which iterates m_nSize times over m_TagVals,
reading poisoned memory (ASAN: 0xbebebebebebebebe = freed-memory fill).

Also fixes: Read() leaks the created pTag when pTag->Read() fails — the
tag is allocated but never assigned to m_TagVals and never deleted.

Crash: IccTagComposite.cpp:1524 — misaligned address 0xbebebebebebebebe
for type 'IccTagPtr' in CIccTagArray::Cleanup().

CWE-908 (Use of Uninitialized Resource)
CWE-416 (Use After Free — poisoned pointer iteration)
CWE-401 (Memory Leak — pTag on failed Read)

--- a/IccProfLib/IccTagComposite.cpp
+++ b/IccProfLib/IccTagComposite.cpp
@@ -1034,6 +1034,10 @@
 CIccTagArray::CIccTagArray(const CIccTagArray &tagAry)
 {
+  // CFL-013: Initialize before conditional to prevent uninitialized
+  // m_TagVals/m_nSize when tagAry.m_nSize == 0 or calloc fails
+  m_TagVals = NULL;
+  m_nSize = 0;
+
   if (tagAry.m_nSize) {
     m_TagVals = (IccTagPtr*)calloc(tagAry.m_nSize, sizeof(IccTagPtr));  // CFL-003: match calloc/free (CWE-762)
     if (!m_TagVals) {
@@ -1300,6 +1304,7 @@
         if (pTag) {
           if (!pTag->Read(tagPos[i].size, pIO)) {
             delete [] tagPos;
+            delete pTag;  // CFL-013: prevent leak of allocated tag on failed Read
             return false;
           }
           m_TagVals[i].ptr = pTag;
